s=title> What Are They Paid For?!</span><hr size=1> I realize that this is perhaps not the best forum for this thread but oh well.  The topic at hand irks me enough and that's all the reason I need.<br>
<br>
After watching this evening's preseason football game on ESPN, something occured to me.  It was a better game than 95% of last year's season games.  There is no drive in professional sports anymore.  In the preseason games, questionable season starters put everything on the line to clinch their spot; ironically making preseason games some of the year's best.<br>
<br>
But it's not just in the arena's of the NFL, it's evident in almost all professional sports.  In the last three years, I've wathced some of my favorite players, in all sports, turn to laccadaisical athletes after signing a juicy long term contract.  It's to the point where I now watch barely any of the NFL games.  My attention has been pulled to college football, where young men do not have fat purses waiting for them after each season, only their pride.  They play every game as if it were their last.  Diving for every ball, running full steam for every play.  Its just something that cannot be found in the NFL anymore.  The same goes for the NHL, MLB, and NBA.<br>
<br>
On top of the rampant lack of desire, we have the corruption of sports by television.  Football games practically revolve around the commercial schedule.    I'm sorry, but I don't give a flying fvck about Dodge or the mayor of Truckville, or Budweiser, etc.<br>
<br>
Through all of this, proffesional sports have become candied and glazed.  Everything is superficial.  Players skip practice all week; score on game day and give their thanks to God or another entity, and then rape or attack someone the following week.  WTF is with that!  All I can say is that someone or something needs to bust out the firehose and spray off the giant steaming pile of shyt that is smothering proffessional sports as we know it.<br>
<br>
These are supposed the world's finest athletes in each of their callings.  They need to prove that they deserve that honor.<br>
<br>
Well now that the fire is burning, I hope someone has got some gas for it.  My apoligies for the inane irelevancy of this post, but I just had to.<br>
<br>
